

🚀 Lab Summary: Local Kubernetes to Windows Browser Network Bridge
📐 Core Architecture Layout
The goal was to access an isolated Kubernetes application inside a Linux Virtual Machine (VM) using Google Chrome on a Windows host machine using a custom local domain name (my-nginx.local).

[Windows Host Machine]                   [Linux Virtual Machine (VM)]
  ├── Google Chrome                        ├── Host-Only Interface (192.168.56.101)
  └── \etc\hosts (my-nginx.local) ───►     └── kubectl port-forward (Port: 8080)
                                                    │ (Tunnels through kube-proxy)
                                                    ▼
                                           [Kubernetes Cluster Layer]
                                               ├── ClusterIP Service
                                               └── 2x Nginx Pods (Frontend)
🛠️ Step-by-Step Execution Guide
Part 1: The Kubernetes Infrastructure (Inside the Linux VM)
1. Create the Manifest File
Save this text as nginx-project.yaml inside your project directory. It defines 2 Nginx application instances and exposes them through an internal ClusterIP load balancer.

YAML
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: nginx-deployment
  labels:
    app: demo-nginx
spec:
  replicas: 2 
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      tier: frontend
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        tier: frontend
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: nginx-container
        image: nginx:latest
        imagePullPolicy: IfNotPresent # Crucial for offline work
        ports:
        - containerPort: 80
---
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: nginx-internal-service
spec:
  type: ClusterIP 
  ports:
  - port: 80        
    targetPort: 80  
  selector:
    tier: frontend  
2. Apply and Verify the Infrastructure

Bash
# Apply the configuration
kubectl apply -f nginx-project.yaml

# Verify your pods are in a running state
kubectl get pods -l tier=frontend

# Inspect your newly created service ClusterIP address
kubectl get svc nginx-internal-service
Part 2: The Network Bridge (Inside the Linux VM)
Because a ClusterIP cannot be reached from outside the VM's internal kernel routing tables, we create a proxy tunnel mapping traffic from all network interfaces down to our cluster service layer.

We pass $HOME/.kube/config explicitly to prevent sudo environment stripping errors.

Bash
# Start a background proxy binding port 8080 on all VM network cards
sudo kubectl --kubeconfig=$HOME/.kube/config port-forward --address 0.0.0.0 svc/nginx-internal-service 8080:80 &

# Find your VM host-only IP network interface address (Look for the 192.168.56.x subnet)
hostname -I
Part 3: Local Local Domain Setup (Inside Windows Command Prompt)
We map the static host-only private IP interface to our domain. This must be executed in a true Administrator Elevated Console.

DOS
:: 1. Navigate to your system directory driving configuration mappings
cd C:\Windows\System32\drivers\etc

:: 2. Safely strip away any read-only attributes keeping the file locked
attrib -r hosts

:: 3. Stream-write the domain mapping to the bottom of the system lookup table
echo 192.168.56.101    my-nginx.local>>hosts

:: 4. Print the output string to ensure the file looks exactly like the blueprint
type hosts
Part 4: Verification and Access (Inside Google Chrome)
Open your web browser and target your application directly by including the custom bridge port string:

Plaintext
http://my-nginx.local:8080


C:\Windows\System32\drivers\etc>powershell -Command "Start-Process notepad 'C:\Windows\System32\drivers\etc\hosts' -Verb RunAs"

C:\Windows\System32\drivers\etc>type hosts
